('Engineering', 'Backend Engineer - Forward Deployed', '', 'Problem Framing & Technical Versatility', 'Focuses on the literal request ("X"). Struggles to uncover the underlying need ("Y") without explicit guidance. Requires significant help to integrate complex systems and needs a detailed plan from a senior to deploy safely. Avoids pushing back.', 'Can understand a workflow if given some documentation. Asks clarifying questions to better understand "X." Can handle basic API integrations but needs support for complex issues (e.g., auth mismatches). Follows existing deployment checklists to ensure safety. Can push back but is not always persuasive.', 'Proactively investigates (e.g., asks "why," shadows users) to uncover the true need ("Y"). Can independently design and implement robust integrations across complex/legacy systems. Knows when and how to push back effectively, presenting data and options to reach a compromise. Independently de-risks complex deployments.', 'Anticipates client needs before they are articulated. Reframes "X vs. Y" into a strategic solution ("Z") that solves the root problem for the long term. Architects reusable solutions to handle classes of integration problems, not just one-offs. Mentors others on how to advise clients and manage technical risk.'),
('Engineering', 'DevOps Engineer', '', 'AWS Fundamentals & Architecture', 'Basic awareness and foundational knowledge. Requires close supervision and detailed guidance. Can identify basic AWS services relevant to the scenario but requires significant guidance to understand how they contribute to high availability, scalability, backups, or disaster recovery. May struggle to articulate basic concepts or provide specific AWS service examples. Has limited awareness of associated costs, complexity, or potential single points of failure.', 'Working knowledge and consistent application. Needs periodic supervision and support for complex tasks. Can describe common AWS services for high availability (e.g., Load Balancers, Auto Scaling Groups), scalability, backups (e.g., EBS snapshots), and disaster recovery (e.g., cross-region replication). Can explain basic architectural patterns such as multi-AZ deployments and fundamental auto-scaling principles. Can articulate basic data replication or redundancy strategies (e.g., RDS, DynamoDB, or S3). May need some support when discussing trade-offs between cost and resiliency, or when addressing more complex scenarios like multi-region deployments or advanced auto-scaling.', 'Comprehensive understanding and independent application. Can handle most complex situations and guide others. Demonstrates a comprehensive understanding of architecting for high availability, scalability, robust backups, and disaster recovery on AWS. Can articulate various strategies, including multi-AZ and multi-region deployments, advanced auto-scaling (e.g., Karpenter on EKS), and cross-region replication for disaster recovery. Can discuss trade-offs in detail, including cost, complexity, and defining and testing RPO (Recovery Point Objective) and RTO (Recovery Time Objective). Provides specific examples of AWS services (e.g., ALB, NLB, RDS, DynamoDB, S3) and their effective application within the HR management platform scenario. Can also discuss cost optimization strategies such as instance rightsizing, advanced cost monitoring, and the use of serverless architectures where appropriate, leveraging tools like AWS Cost Explorer or CloudWatch metrics.', 'Complete mastery, innovation, and leadership. Sets standards, develops new approaches, and mentors others. Exhibits complete mastery in designing and implementing highly available, scalable, resilient, and cost-optimized AWS architectures. Can innovate and develop new approaches to solve complex architectural challenges, setting standards for the organization. Provides a comprehensive overview of multi-AZ/multi-region deployments, advanced auto-scaling groups, various data replication/redundancy strategies, and robust disaster recovery plans with clearly defined RPO/RTO. Discusses trade-offs in depth, including cost considerations, performance vs. cost, and security aspects (e.g., CloudFront or WAF for edge delivery and security). Can lead discussions on advanced cost optimization strategies, including the use of AWS Cost Explorer, CloudWatch metrics, and third-party cost analysis tools, and effectively mentor others in these areas. May reference tools like Terraform or Crossplane to deploy architecture predictably and repetitively across environments, and discuss ephemeral vs. persistent storage.'),
('Engineering', 'DevOps Engineer', '', 'Kubernates Expertise', 'Basic awareness and foundational knowledge. Requires close supervision and detailed guidance. Can identify basic Kubernetes concepts (e.g., Pods, Deployments) but requires significant guidance to understand how they contribute to release automation or reliability. May struggle to articulate basic deployment strategies or the importance of automated testing.', 'Working knowledge and consistent application. Needs periodic supervision and support for complex tasks. Can describe common Kubernetes deployment strategies (e.g., rolling updates) and the role of CI/CD in release automation. Understands the importance of automated testing and basic monitoring. May need some support when discussing advanced deployment strategies (blue/green, canary) or comprehensive rollback plans.', 'Comprehensive understanding and independent application. Can handle most complex situations and guide others. Demonstrates a comprehensive understanding of designing a release process for Kubernetes that minimizes downtime and ensures reliability. Can articulate various deployment strategies (e.g., blue/green, canary releases, rolling updates), the role of immutable infrastructure, and GitOps principles (e.g., ArgoCD, FluxCD). Can discuss automated testing, monitoring, and robust rollback strategies.', 'Complete mastery, innovation, and leadership. Sets standards, develops new approaches, and mentors others. Exhibits complete mastery in designing and implementing highly reliable and automated release processes for Kubernetes. Can innovate and develop new approaches to solve complex release challenges. Provides a comprehensive explanation of a robust CI/CD pipeline integrated with Kubernetes, covering advanced deployment strategies (blue/green, canary), automated testing, observability, and a well-defined rollback plan. Discusses the use of service meshes (Istio, Linkerd) for traffic management and mentors others in best practices.'),
('Engineering', 'DevOps Engineer', '', 'Terraform & Infrastructure as code', 'Basic awareness and foundational knowledge. Requires close supervision and detailed guidance. Can identify basic Terraform concepts (e.g., resources, providers) but requires significant guidance to understand how they contribute to reusability, maintainability, or disaster recovery. May struggle to articulate basic module usage or state management.', 'Working knowledge and consistent application. Needs periodic supervision and support for complex tasks. Can describe common Terraform practices for organizing code (e.g., basic module usage), managing state (e.g., local state, basic remote state), and understands the importance of IaC for disaster recovery. May need some support when discussing advanced module versioning or multi-region DR strategies.', 'Comprehensive understanding and independent application. Can handle most complex situations and guide others. Demonstrates a comprehensive understanding of organizing Terraform code for reusability and maintainability (e.g., well-structured modules, workspaces). Can articulate strategies for managing remote state (e.g., S3 backend) and versioning modules. Can also explain how to leverage IaC for robust multi-region disaster recovery, including automated provisioning and DR drills.', 'Complete mastery, innovation, and leadership. Sets standards, develops new approaches, and mentors others. Exhibits complete mastery in designing and implementing highly reusable, maintainable, and secure Terraform projects. Can innovate and develop new approaches for complex IaC challenges, including advanced state management, CI/CD integration, and multi-region DR strategies (e.g., blue/green, canary deployments for DR). Provides detailed explanations of secrets management, security best practices, and compliance in Terraform. May mention tools like Terragrunt or Atlantis for advanced workflows.'),
('Engineering', 'DevOps Engineer', '', 'Operations', 'Basic awareness and foundational knowledge. Requires close supervision and detailed guidance. Can identify basic operational concepts (e.g., monitoring, backups) but requires significant guidance to understand how they contribute to uptime, incident response, or automation. May struggle to articulate basic monitoring tools or incident management steps.', 'Working knowledge and consistent application. Needs periodic supervision and support for complex tasks. Can describe common monitoring tools (e.g., CloudWatch, basic Grafana), basic incident management steps, and the importance of automation. Understands basic concepts of dashboards, alerts, and on-call rotations. May need some support when discussing advanced alerting strategies or comprehensive incident response plans.', 'Comprehensive understanding and independent application. Can handle most complex situations and guide others. Demonstrates a comprehensive understanding of designing and implementing monitoring and alerting strategies (e.g., Prometheus, Grafana, Datadog, ELK stack). Can articulate robust incident management processes, including communication plans, root cause analysis, and blameless post-mortems. Can identify and propose automation for repetitive tasks, discussing various scripting languages and tools.', 'Complete mastery, innovation, and leadership. Sets standards, develops new approaches, and mentors others. Exhibits complete mastery in designing and implementing highly reliable and automated operational processes. Can innovate and develop new approaches for complex monitoring, incident management, and automation challenges. Provides a detailed strategy for comprehensive monitoring (infrastructure, application, business-level), advanced alerting (PagerDuty, Opsgenie), and a blameless post-mortem culture. Emphasizes observability, shift-left monitoring, and secure, testable, and maintainable automation.'),
